{{Use British English|date=October 2016}} {{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}} {{Infobox person | name = Hope Loring | image = Hope Loring - Jun 1919 MPW.jpg | caption = Loring in 1919 | birth_date = 29 January 1894 | birth_place = England | death_date = {{death year and age|1959|1894}} | death_place = [[Majorca]], Spain | yearsactive = 1918-1931 | occupation = Screenwriter }}
'''Hope Loring''' (29 January 1894 &ndash; 1959), was an English [[screenwriter]]. <ref>{{cite book |last=Tibbetts |first=John |date=23 July 2010 |title=American Classic Screen Interviews |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=V-MwbvCRnFcC&dq=hope+loring+screenwriter&source=gbs_navlinks_s |location= |publisher=Scarecrow Press |page=93 |isbn=0810876752 |access-date=24 April 2015 }}</ref> She wrote for 63 films between 1918 and 1931.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://wfpp.cdrs.columbia.edu/pioneer/ccp-hope-loring/ | title=Hope Loring | work=Women Film Pioneers Project | publisher=Center for Digital Research and Scholarship, Columbia University Libraries | first=Annie | last=Berke | date=27 September 2013 | accessdate=30 October 2016 }}</ref> She was born in [[England]] and died in [[Majorca]], [[Spain]]. She was married to fellow screenwriter and producer [[Louis D. Lighton]].
